 material is elevated by the director’s refined visual style, typified in the elaborate moving camera shots for which he is famous.</p>\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Max Ophuls","producer":"John Houseman","writer":"Howard Koch","featuring":"Joan Fontaine, Louis Jourdan, Mady Christians"},"year":"1948","nameAndYear":"Letter from an Unknown Woman (1948)","links":{"player":"","southbank":""},"player":null,"performances":[],"tags":[],"productionCountries":"USA","runningTime":87,"sightAndSound":null,"products":[]}},{"rank":169,"tied":true,"film":{"uuid":"4af384f2-7ba5-5984-85fd-204e8a9b7a21","image":{"base":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/","relative":"2022-07/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg","main":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/responsive/public/2022-07/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg/1920x1080-cropped/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg","thumb":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/responsive/public/2022-07/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg/960x540-cropped/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg","preload":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/styles/responsive/public/2022-07/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg/96x54-cropped/charulata-1964-woman-holding-theatre-binoculars.jpg","altText":null},"name":"Charulata","url":"/film/4af384f2-7ba5-5984-85fd-204e8a9b7a21/charulata","summary":{"text":"Satyajit Ray’s sublime portrait of a bored housewife living in 19th-century Bengal.","html":"<p>Satyajit Ray’s sublime portrait of a bored housewife living in 19th-century Bengal.</p>\r\n"},"fullDescription":"<p>Satyajit Ray’s own favourite of his films, Charulata, is set in late 19-century Bengal and boasts a marvellously vital Victorian heroine: Charulata, spellbindingly portrayed by Madhabi Mukherjee, is beautiful, intellectual and dangerously&nbsp;bored.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Racing from window to window in her vast, ornate mansion, Charulata spies hungrily on the outside world through opera glasses. Her wealthy husband Bhupati (Sailen Mukherjee), the high-minded editor of a political journal, is too preoccupied with the latest tax legislation and the forthcoming English election (Disraeli v Gladstone) to pay much attention to his wife. Somewhat unwisely, he invites his charming younger cousin Amal (Soumitra Chatterjee, who previously starred in Ray’s The World of Apu) to come and keep her company. An aspiring writer who shares Charulata’s passion for poetry, Amal is keen to encourage her literary&nbsp;talent...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a household of seething, suppressed emotions, subtly revealed by Subrata Mitra’s eloquent camera. A richly atmospheric soundtrack – bird song, horses’ hooves, the cry of the kulfi vendor – evokes the wider world, while Ray’s wistful score and the romantic songs beloved of Charulata and Amal heighten the sense of&nbsp;longing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adapted from a 1901 novella, Nastanirh (The Broken Nest) by the great Bengali writer Rabindranath Tagore, Charulata was described by its director as “the one film I would make the same way if I had to do it&nbsp;again”.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enthusiastically received at home and abroad, Charulata was awarded the Silver Bear for Best Direction at the Berlin Film Festival of 1965.</p>\r\n","quote":null,"credits":{"director":"Satyajit Ray","producer":"R.D. Bansal","writer":"Satyajit Ray","featuring":"Soumitra Chatterjee, Madhabi Mukherjee, Sailen Mukherjee"},"year":"1964","nameAndYear":"Charulata (1964)","links":{"player":"","southbank":""},"player":null,"performances":[],"tags":[],"productionCountries":"India","runningTime":124,"sightAndSound":null,"products":[]}},{"rank":169,"tied":true,"film":{"uuid":"48f84a16-0530-544f-b591-0d564249dd43","image":{"base":"https://core-cms.bfi.org.uk/sites/default/files/","relative":"2022-03/the-good-the-bad-and-the-ugly-1966-clint-eastwood-neck-in-noose.jpg","main":"https://c